Here is an example of a simple login system using JavaScript, HTML, and CSS:

**index.html**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Login</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <div class="login-container">
        <h2>Login</h2>
        <form id="login-form">
            <label for="username">Username:</label>
            <input type="text" id="username" name="username"><br><br>
            <label for="password">Password:</label>
            <input type="password" id="password" name="password"><br><br>
            <button type="submit">Login</button>
        </form>
    </div>

    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```
**style.css**
```css
.login-container {
    width: 300px;
    margin: 50px auto;
    background-color: #f0f0f0;
    padding: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
}

label {
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
}

input[type="text"], input[type="password"] {
    width: 100%;
    height: 40px;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
    padding: 10px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
}
```
**script.js**
```javascript
// Get the form and inputs
const loginForm = document.getElementById('login-form');
const usernameInput = document.getElementById('username');
const passwordInput = document.getElementById('password');

// Set up event listener for form submission
loginForm.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();

    // Get the input values
    const username = usernameInput.value.trim();
    const password = passwordInput.value.trim();

    // Validate the inputs
    if (!username || !password) {
        alert('Please enter both username and password');
        return;
    }

    // Check against stored credentials (in a real app, this would be a database)
    const storedCredentials = [
        { username: 'admin', password: 'password123' },
        { username: 'user1', password: 'password456' }
    ];

    const storedCredential = storedCredentials.find((credential) => {
        return credential.username === username && credential.password === password;
    });

    if (storedCredential) {
        alert('Login successful!');
        // Redirect to a protected page or do something else
        window.location.href = '/protected-page.html';
    } else {
        alert('Invalid credentials');
    }
});
```
This code creates a simple login form with two inputs for username and password. When the user submits the form, it checks against stored credentials (in this case, a hardcoded array). If the input credentials match one of the stored credentials, it displays an "Login successful!" message and redirects to a protected page (replace `'/protected-page.html'` with your own path).

Please note that in a real-world application, you would want to use a more secure method for storing and comparing passwords, such as hashing and salting.

Also, this code is just an example and should not be used as-is in production. You should always follow best practices for security and user authentication.
